<br>
Sure, I found most of the latest books slow and kinda boring, but I was still mostly enjoying the series. I'd just skim a bit over any sections that contained TOO much braid-tugging and skirt-smoothing.<br>
<br>
But this latest book was a slap in the face.<br>
<br>
** SPOILERS BELOW **<br>
<br>
Ok, going back and seeing everyone's reaction to Rand cleansing saidin was ok, but as an overall plot, we're essentially at the exact same place we were at the end of the last book. <br>
<br>
There was so much meaningless crap in this book. There was no plot development. What did I get out of this latest book, main plotwise? <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>There are a few alliances about to happen... good guys and Seanchan, Aes Sedai and Asha'man</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. That's it. Whoa! What a shock! As if anyone reading didn't know that was gonna happen anyway before the last battle.<br>
<br>
There was NOTHING ELSE. A ghost town that meant nothing. Faile is still stuck with the Shaido. Elayne is still trying to become Queen of Andor. Egwene is still sitting outside Tar Valon, wondering how to take it. Mat is still fleeing Ebou Dar with his captive bride-to-be. Rand is still sitting around brooding. He did NOTHING in this book. NOTHING.<br>
<br>
I'm just so disappointed. I truly loved this series. I didn't even mind a few of his later, slower books. Sure they were basically stagnant, but RJ at least always came through at the end and threw in some huge plot development in the last few pages.<br>
<br>
He even almost totally abandoned one of my favorite plot devices he's always used... showing us glimpses of the bad guys, what they're doing and planning. There were a couple of instances, but they were dry and boring. Alviarin got demoted, Daved Hanlon kills a random thief, hurray? No Forsaken. No Moridin. Half a page of Shaidar Haran. No renegade Asha'man. No Black Ajah, besides passing references.<br>
<br>
