<br>
I still think everything up to book 6 was great.  I loved them and kept rereading them when a new one would come out.  These books are incredible in how they described people and places so well you almost thought you were there.  You got to know the characters very well and really started to understand what made them tick.  The plot itself was very intricate but also easy to follow (sort of similar to the B5 story arc - yes, I'm a dork) and you could see signs of preplanning for later events 2 or 3 books ahead.<br>
<br>
7 and 8 started getting really fractured and tried to follow a million different subplots with a billion different minor characters.  You needed an encyclopedia just to keep track of what was going on, and the books couldn't devote more than 1 or 2 chapters per plot line because there were so many.  This caused the overall plot to really bog down but at least it was moving.  Stuff happened in these books, you could almost argue that too much stuff happened and that Jordan could have focused more on the main characters.<br>
<br>
Book 9 was getting much better.  A few less subplots followed, no new minor characters introduced and a basic story line that advanced the overall plot.  I was really getting hopeful here.  The end of the book was done well and had major impact on everyone.  Thoroughly enjoyed it.<br>
<br>
Book 10 was utter garbage.  680 pages of people talking and nothing happening.  I'm not a big action freak and I don't need glorious battles at the end of every book, but I do expect some sort of plot advancement.  What I got was 680 pages of filler with 600 pages of minor detail descriptions and 2 sentences of plot.  Each of the book's 5 major sections could be summed up in a well written paragraph or two.  Very disappointing.<br>
<br>
Also, has anyone else noticed that the mighty Aes Sedai, who are supposed to be some of the toughest, most ruthless and most controlled women in this world, have all become simpering idiots who have emotional breakdowns at every opportunity and get bullied by every farm wife and merchant?  The dark one apperantly has the planning and strategic skills of a 6 year old with ADD, Rand has the observational and deductive skills of a blind and deaf chimp and Egwene is running more scams and shady dealings than the entire US congress combined.  Maybe I missed all this in previous books because the plot kept me interested, but the last book really made me aware of how much this series was lacking lately.  Doubt I'll pick up the next book.  <p><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-size:xx-small;"><br>
